SIMPLE: sanatory
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sanatory
<hw>San"a*to*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>sanatorius</ets>, fr. L. <ets>sanare</ets> to heal. See
<er>Sanable</er>.]</ety> <def>Conducive to health; tending to cure;
healing; curative; sanative.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Sanatory</qex> ordinances for the protection of public
health, such as quarantine, fever hospitals, draining, etc.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Sanatory</xex> and <xex>sanitary</xex> should not
be confounded. <xex>Sanatory</xex> signifies <xex>conducive to
health</xex>, while <xex>sanitary</xex> has the more general meaning of
<xex>pertaining to health</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sanbenito</ent>⟦br⟧
